@startuml Detailed_Comparison
!theme plain

title Protected vs Private Inheritance - Complete Comparison

package "1. Protected Inheritance" #lightgreen {
  
  card Setup1 [
    **Code:**
    class Base {
      protected: int x;
      public: int y;
    };
    
    class Middle : protected Base {
      // x is protected
      // y is protected
    };
    
    class GrandChild : public Middle {
      // ✅ CAN access x
      // ✅ CAN access y
    };
  ]
  
  card Access1 [
    **Access in GrandChild:**
    
    void GrandChild::method() {
      x = 10;  // ✅ OK!
      y = 20;  // ✅ OK!
    }
    
    **Inheritance continues!**
  ]
  
  Setup1 -down-> Access1
}

package "2. Private Inheritance" #pink {
  
  card Setup2 [
    **Code:**
    class Base {
      protected: int x;
      public: int y;
    };
    
    class Middle : private Base {
      // x is private
      // y is private
    };
    
    class GrandChild : public Middle {
      // ❌ CANNOT access x
      // ❌ CANNOT access y
    };
  ]
  
  card Access2 [
    **Access in GrandChild:**
    
    void GrandChild::method() {
      x = 10;  // ❌ ERROR!
      y = 20;  // ❌ ERROR!
    }
    
    **Inheritance STOPS!**
  ]
  
  Setup2 -down-> Access2
}

note bottom
  **Key Difference:**
  
  Protected: Allows FURTHER inheritance
  Private: STOPS inheritance chain
  
  Both prevent outside access,
  but behave differently for derived classes!
end note

@enduml